{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti Chapter 11 in this corpus covers only the first six verses (verses 11.1–11.6), which discuss gifts to Brahmins, snātakas (those who have completed Vedic study), and rules for kings and sacrifices.[^1]**\n\nNo passages in the available portion of Manusmṛti (or elsewhere in the Falsafa corpus) mention cats (English \"cat\" or Sanskrit \"mārjāra\"), killing animals, or expiations specifically for accidentally killing a cat. Searches across the corpus for terms like \"cat\", \"kill cat\", \"killing a cat\", \"mārjāra\", and related phrases (\"expiation animal\", \"kill animal\") yielded no relevant results.[^2]\n\nThe full Manusmṛti Chapter 11 (traditionally ~266 verses on expiations/prāyaścitta) is not fully available here, so this specific prescription cannot be answered from the corpus.\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 11 (translation), [chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/11/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Corpus-wide searches returned unrelated results (e.g., from *Andreas* or *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*), none matching the query.",
